article.headline: Sutton-Brown scores career-high 22
article.linkText: Resurgent Sting too hot to handle for Miracle
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Dawn Staley sat alone in the back of the
locker room, craning her neck to see the WNBA scores scroll across
the bottom of the television set. When she couldn't make them all
out, teammates shouted updates.

	   The Charlotte Sting are keeping a close eye on the competition
in their bid to repeat as Eastern Conference champions.

	   "We want to get as many wins as we can and go through this
second half of the season really pushing toward the playoffs and
reminding everyone we're still the top team,'' Staley said after
the Sting's 89-62 victory over the Orlando Miracle on Wednesday
night.

	   "We're right there and we should be the team that rises because
we're veterans.''

	   Tammy Sutton-Brown scored a career-high 22 points, Andrea
Stinson had 13 points and eight assists, Allison Feaster scored 13
points and Staley added 11 points and eight assists as the Sting
made a strong statement to start the second half of the season.

	   Charlotte (12-9) shot 60 percent for the game and made 10
3-pointers -- three from league-leader Feaster -- while coming out of
the All-Star break by closing within two games of division-leading
Washington.

	   "We played like the defending Eastern Conference champions,''
Sutton-Brown said. "That's what we have to do if we want to get
back there. We have our legs back from the break and we're ready to
roll.''

	   Wendy Palmer scored 15 points to lead Orlando (9-10). The
Miracle lost their fourth straight game and seventh of nine to fall
below .500 for the first time this season.

	   "They are the Eastern Conference champions for a reason,'' said
Orlando coach Dee Brown. "We are trying to get where they are
at.''

	   The second half was marred by a fight between Charlotte's Summer
Erb and Orlando's Jessie Hicks. The two were battling for a loose
ball with 9:08 to play when Erb apparently fouled Hicks but didn't
get the call.

	   The two began pushing and shoving and Hicks threw a punch at
Erb's cheek. Erb swiped back but missed and was allowed to stay in
the game while Hicks was ejected with Charlotte leading 68-50.

	   Hicks was unavailable for comment and Erb denied she did
anything to provoke it.

	   "We just got tangled up, it's a physical game,'' she said.
"That's all, there's no history there.''

	   Erb made a free throw after the altercation and Charlotte Smith
hit a 3-pointer to stretch the Sting's lead to 72-50.

	   It was the second fight in the WNBA in less than a week.

	   Latasha Byears of the Los Angeles Sparks was suspended two games
and fined $1,000 and Michelle Marciniak of the Seattle Storm got a
one-game suspension and a $500 fine for their fight last Thursday.

	   Erb said the previous penalties caused her to think before
retaliating against Hicks.

	   "I just let it go,'' she said. "You've got to, the fines are
too big and the paychecks are too small.''

	   The Sting took control of the game early with an 18-9 run that
gave them their first double-digit lead.

	   Sutton-Brown, fresh off an appearance in Monday's All-Star game,
scored nine points in the run and blocked Nykesha Sales' shot while
helping Charlotte to a 26-16 lead with 11:03 to play.

	   Sutton-Brown had no trouble getting around Clarisse Machanguana,
the center who Sutton-Brown beat out for a spot in Charlotte's
starting lineup as a rookie last year, while shooting 6-for-8 from
the field in the first half.

	   She went into the break with 13 points, including a 7-foot
jumper that gave Charlotte a 45-31 halftime lead.
